  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Django Selectors Pattern</title>

    <summary>Keyword-only functions in selectors.py that encapsulate read operations, return QuerySet with select_related/prefetch_related, and prevent N+1 queries. Query logic belongs in selectors, not in views, serializers, or tests.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Without selectors, query logic scatters across views, serializers, and test setup. The same N+1-prone pattern gets copy-pasted in five places. A single optimization (adding a prefetch) must be applied everywhere. With selectors, changing one function propagates the fix automatically to all callers — views, tasks, admin, management commands. Selectors also make N+1 testing straightforward: the selector's test can assert the query count using django_assert_num_queries.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any list query with filtering, ordering, or pagination.</item>
        <item>Fetching a single object by ID or unique field, especially with related data.</item>
        <item>Queries with select_related or prefetch_related for related model data.</item>
        <item>Queries used in more than one place (view, task, admin, management command).</item>
        <item>Queries that need N+1 prevention guaranteed across all usage points.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Simple Model.objects.get(pk=pk) with no related data — inline is fine if only used once.</item>
        <item>Write operations — those belong in services.</item>
        <item>Annotations purely for display (computed fields in serializers via SerializerMethodField).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <rules>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Selector functions MUST use keyword-only arguments (asterisk). List selectors return QuerySet[Model]. Single-object selectors return Model and raise Model.DoesNotExist or NotFoundError if not found — never return None from a "get" selector. Selectors MUST include all prefetch_related and select_related calls needed for the data their callers will access.</statement>
        <rationale>Returning QuerySet allows the caller to chain additional filters without making a new query. Consistent exception behavior (DoesNotExist raised, not None returned) prevents None-check errors downstream. Bundling all prefetches in the selector guarantees N+1 prevention for every caller.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use select_related for ForeignKey and OneToOne relations (single JOIN). Use prefetch_related for ManyToMany and reverse ForeignKey relations (separate query). Use Prefetch() object when the related queryset needs its own filter, ordering, or prefetch.</statement>
        <rationale>select_related generates a SQL JOIN — right for FK/OneToOne where one related object per row. prefetch_related generates a separate query — right for M2M / reverse FK where multiple related objects per row. A blanket prefetch_related on an FK wastes round trips; a blanket select_related on a reverse FK causes cartesian product blowup.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use .exists() instead of .count() > 0 or len(queryset) > 0 for existence checks. Use .annotate() for aggregations that should be fetched in the same query. Use F() expressions for field references in filters and annotations.</statement>
        <rationale>exists() generates SELECT 1 ... LIMIT 1 — O(1) DB cost. count() > 0 generates SELECT COUNT(*) — O(N) DB cost. len(queryset) materializes the entire queryset in Python memory just to check if it's non-empty.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </rules>

    <example type="good" title="List selector with optimization">
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# apps/orders/selectors.py
from django.db.models import QuerySet, Prefetch

from apps.orders.models import Order, OrderItem


def order_list_for_user(
    *,
    user: "User",
    status: str | None = None,
    limit: int | None = None,
) -> QuerySet[Order]:
    """
    Get orders for a user with optimized queries.

    Args:
        user: The user to get orders for
        status: Optional status filter
        limit: Optional result limit

    Returns:
        Optimized QuerySet of orders with prefetched items
    """
    queryset = (
        Order.objects
        .filter(user=user)
        .select_related("shipping_method")
        .prefetch_related(
            Prefetch(
                "items",
                queryset=OrderItem.objects.select_related("product"),
            )
        )
        .order_by("-created_at")
    )

    if status:
        queryset = queryset.filter(status=status)

    if limit:
        queryset = queryset[:limit]

    return queryset
      ]]></code>
    </example>

    <example type="bad" title="Query in view (anti-pattern)">
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# BAD — query in view, no optimization, duplicated across views
class OrderListView(APIView):
    def get(self, request):
        orders = Order.objects.filter(user=request.user)  # N+1 when serializing items
        return Response(OrderSerializer(orders, many=True).data)
      ]]></code>
      <note>Query logic in view: cannot be reused, no N+1 prevention, change must be applied in every view that lists orders.</note>
    </example>

    <example type="good" title="Single-object selector with optional ownership filter">
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def order_get_by_id(
    *,
    order_id: int,
    user: "User | None" = None,
) -> Order:
    """
    Get single order by ID.

    Args:
        order_id: The order primary key
        user: Optional user for ownership verification

    Returns:
        Order instance

    Raises:
        Order.DoesNotExist: If not found or not owned by user
    """
    queryset = Order.objects.select_related(
        "user",
        "shipping_method",
    ).prefetch_related("items__product")

    if user:
        queryset = queryset.filter(user=user)

    return queryset.get(id=order_id)
      ]]></code>
    </example>

    <section name="advanced-queries">
      <p>Selectors for complex query patterns:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Selector with annotations and complex prefetch">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from django.db.models import Count, Prefetch, Q


def order_list_with_summary(*, user: "User") -> QuerySet[Order]:
    """Get orders with item counts and product details."""
    return (
        Order.objects
        .filter(user=user)
        .annotate(items_count=Count("items"))
        .prefetch_related(
            Prefetch(
                "items",
                queryset=OrderItem.objects.select_related("product"),
            )
        )
    )


def user_list_with_recent_orders(*, days: int = 30) -> QuerySet["User"]:
    """Get users with orders in the last N days, annotated with order count."""
    from django.utils import timezone
    from datetime import timedelta

    cutoff = timezone.now() - timedelta(days=days)

    return (
        User.objects
        .filter(orders__created_at__gte=cutoff)
        .annotate(recent_order_count=Count("orders", filter=Q(orders__created_at__gte=cutoff)))
        .distinct()
        .order_by("-recent_order_count")
    )
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Efficient existence check">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# GOOD — efficient existence check
def order_has_pending_payment(*, user: "User") -> bool:
    """Check if user has any orders pending payment."""
    return Order.objects.filter(
        user=user, status=OrderStatus.PENDING
    ).exists()


# BAD — fetches all data just to check existence
def order_has_pending_payment_bad(*, user: "User") -> bool:
    return Order.objects.filter(user=user, status='pending').count() > 0
        ]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Bulk query optimization">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# GOOD — bulk update using F() expression
from django.db.models import F
from decimal import Decimal


def product_increase_prices(*, increase_pct: Decimal) -> int:
    """Increase all product prices by percentage. Returns updated count."""
    return Product.objects.update(
        price=F("price") * (1 + increase_pct),
        updated_at=timezone.now(),
    )


# GOOD — bulk update with specific per-record values
def product_bulk_update_prices(*, product_prices: dict[int, Decimal]) -> int:
    """Update multiple products with specific prices."""
    products = Product.objects.filter(id__in=product_prices.keys())

    for product in products:
        product.price = product_prices[product.id]

    Product.objects.bulk_update(products, ["price", "updated_at"])
    return len(products)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="n-plus-one-detection">
      <p>Always test selectors for N+1 queries using django_assert_num_queries fixture from pytest-django:</p>
      <example type="good" title="N+1 test for selector">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
class TestOrderListForUser:
    def test_no_n_plus_one_queries(self, db, django_assert_num_queries):
        """Selector uses optimal number of queries."""
        user = UserFactory()
        OrderFactory.create_batch(5, user=user)

        with django_assert_num_queries(2):  # 1 for orders, 1 for items (prefetch)
            orders = list(order_list_for_user(user=user))
            for order in orders:
                list(order.items.all())  # Access related data — must not trigger new queries
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Selector uses keyword-only arguments.</check>
      <check>List selectors return QuerySet[Model], not list.</check>
      <check>Single-object selectors raise DoesNotExist, not return None.</check>
      <check>All ForeignKey traversals in callers are covered by select_related in the selector.</check>
      <check>All reverse FK / M2M traversals are covered by prefetch_related in the selector.</check>
      <check>Existence checks use .exists(), not count() > 0 or len().</check>
      <check>Selector is tested for N+1 using django_assert_num_queries.</check>
    </checklist>

